      <subsection xml:id="subsec-1-1-1-first-program">
        <title> First Program </title>
        <p> A traditional first program displays the text <c>Hello world.</c> or some variation. 
          Python uses the function <c> print() </c> to display output, making the program simple.
        </p>
        
        

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            print("Hello world!")
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p> Click the <q> evaluate </q> button above to run the embedded Python code. 
          Note that snippets of Python code embedded in the textbook will always have a similar formatting, with the option to <q>evaluate</q>, 
          that is <em>run</em>, the program at the end. 
        </p>

        <p>
          A <term> variable </term> is like a container that can be used to store information or data. 
          In Python you assign a variable using <c> = </c>.  
          The same function <c>print()</c> can be used to display the value of a variable. 
          For example run the Python code below. 
        </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            a = 2*3
            print(a)
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p>
          Now change the value of the variable <em>a</em> by adding 5 in the above code and see how the output changes.
        </p>

        <p>
          Variables can be named using letters, underscores, numbers, etc. 
          Just be sure to use the exact same name to call your variable. 
          For example, the following code has a syntax error. 
        </p>

        <p> Can you see it? </p>

        <p> Try to run the code as is and see what happens. </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            Intro = "Hello again, world!"
            print(intro)
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p> Edit the above code to fix the bug so the code runs correctly. </p>

        <p>
          Python recognizes simple arithmetic symbols like <c>+ -, *, /</c>.  
        </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            sum_and_product = (3+4+5)*2
            print(sum_and_product)

            nine_cubed = 9**3
            print(nine_cubed)
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p> Change the value of the variable to try out some basic calculations in the box below. 
          You can use the standard order of operations and parentheses (PEMDAS) for your input. 
        </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            arithmetic = (9+3)/3
            print(arithmetic)
          </input>
        </sage>

